# Method

## Data


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
#0. Preparation ----

# Load packages
pacman::p_load(haven, #Read sav database
               tidyverse, #Data manipulation
               janitor, #Clean columns
               sjlabelled, #Labels manipulation
               ltm, #Cronbach alpha
               summarytools, #Descriptive tables
               gt, #Tables
               sjPlot,
               labelled 
               )

options(digits = 1) #round results to 2 digits

# Read 
raw_2015 <- read_sav("input/2015_survey_raw.sav") %>% clean_names()
raw_2023 <- read_sav("input/2023_survey_raw.sav") %>% clean_names()

#Recode 2015 communities
raw_2015$comuna <- add_labels(raw_2015$comuna, labels = c(`LA TIRANA` = 23))
raw_2015$comuna <- add_labels(raw_2015$comuna, labels = c(`LA POBLACIÓN` = 9))

#To upper 2023 zones labels
raw_2023 <- raw_2023 %>% mutate(zona_rural=toupper(to_label(zona_rural)))

# Filter zones measured in both studies
raw_2023 <- raw_2023 %>% filter(tipo_zona==2)
comunas_2023<-get_labels(raw_2023$zona_rural) 
raw_2015 <- raw_2015 %>% filter(to_label(comuna)%in%comunas_2023)

# 99 to NA
raw_2015[raw_2015==99]<-NA
raw_2023[raw_2023==99]<-NA
```
:::


The data compared in this study are derived from two surveys on digital inclusion in Chile. The first survey was conducted between March and April 2015, covering 22 rural communities, and comprises 1000 cases. Meanwhile, the second survey was carried out between August and September 2023, encompassing 11 rural communes and 6 urban centers, and contains 1200 cases. The 11 rural communities visited in 2023 were part of the 2015 survey sample, originating from the northern, central, and southern regions of Chile, with less than 1000 inhabitants (averaging 40-50 households per village). These communities are isolated villages that, between September 2010 and December 2011, benefited from the "Todo Chile Comunicado" initiative, a public-private program that provided subsidies for the installation of 3G wireless infrastructure. For this research, cases from these communities were extracted from both databases to enable a comparison of digital inclusion trends over time. [^1]

[^1]: The 11 rural zones studied are referred to as LOS MAQUIS, DOROTEA, INCA DE ORO, LA POBLACIÓN, LA TIRANA, CAMIÑA, TUMBES, LA LAGUNA, TEGUALDA, PUERTO FUY, TABUNCO

In both surveys, the data collection technique employed was route sampling, as the residences in the villages are geographically dispersed and no sampling frame lists were available. The measures used do not form part of a panel survey; therefore, while the analyses reveal longitudinal trends, there is a possibility that the observed changes could be attributed to participant turnover.

The 2015 sample comprises 598 cases, while the 2023 sample comprises 449. Table @tbl-communities presents the distribution by zone for both years.


::: {#tbl-communities .cell tbl-cap='Total cases by rural community'}

```{.r .cell-code}
inner_join(
count(to_label(raw_2015),comuna) %>% rename(Comuna=comuna),
count(to_label(raw_2023),zona_rural) %>% rename(Comuna=zona_rural),
      by="Comuna") %>% rename(N_2015=n.x,N_2023=n.y) %>% 
  rbind(.,as.list(c(Comuna="TOTAL",N_2015=sum(.$N_2015),N_2023=sum(.$N_2023))))%>%



 gt()%>%
  tab_spanner(label = "N por año", columns = c(N_2015,N_2023))%>%
  cols_label(N_2015="2015",
             N_2023="2023")
```

